To subtract the random combinatorial backgrounds and long-range correlations (dominated by hydrodynamic flow in PbPb and momentum conservation constraints in pp events), we employ a sideband subtraction technique in which these backgrounds are approximated by the measured two--dimensional correlations in the range $1.5<\abs{\Delta\eta}<3.0$.   Based on a CMS study that shows no appreciable variation of the elliptic flow for charged particles with $\pt^\text{trk} > 1$\GeV in the $\Delta\eta$ interval of $\pm$3.0 relevant for the present analysis~\cite{v2_HIN_11_012}, the Fourier harmonics are assumed to be constant in $\Delta\eta$. This background distribution in relative azimuthal angle (integrated over $1.5<\abs{\Delta\eta}<3.0$) is then fitted with a function modeling harmonic flow plus a term to capture the (Gaussian or sharper) peak at $\Delta\phi = \pi$ associated with the (smeared) jet opposite to the jet under study:

